From: conda-forge
Subject: [PATCH] Disable job objects in process library to fix builderMainLoop error

GHC 9.2.8 bundles process-1.6.16.0 which has a bug in Windows job object
handling that causes "builderMainLoop: invalid argument" errors. The bug
was fixed in process-1.6.18.0 but we cannot easily upgrade the bundled library.

This patch disables job object creation in c_runInteractiveProcess by treating
useJobObject as always false. This is safe because job objects are an
optimization for process management (tracking child process trees), not a
required feature.

IMPORTANT: The original patch that made createJob() return NULL immediately
was WRONG because the calling code treats NULL as an error condition. This
patch instead modifies the calling code to skip job object creation entirely.

The Stage 1 GHC we build will contain this patched process library, so when
it compiles Stage 2 GHC, the builderMainLoop error won't occur.

See:
- https://hackage.haskell.org/package/process-1.6.24.0/changelog
- https://github.com/haskell/cabal/issues/7309
- https://github.com/haskell/process/issues/273

diff --git a/libraries/process/cbits/win32/runProcess.c b/libraries/process/cbits/win32/runProcess.c
--- a/libraries/process/cbits/win32/runProcess.c
+++ b/libraries/process/cbits/win32/runProcess.c
@@ -361,17 +361,12 @@ runInteractiveProcess (wchar_t *cmd, wchar_t *workingDirectory, wchar_t *environ
     /* If we're going to use a job object, then we have to create
        the thread suspended.
        See Note [Windows exec interaction].  */
-    if (useJobObject)
-    {
-        dwFlags |= CREATE_SUSPENDED;
-        *hJob = createJob();
-        if (!*hJob)
-        {
-            goto cleanup_err;
-        }
-    } else {
-        *hJob = NULL;
-    }
+    // CONDA-FORGE: Always disable job objects on Windows to avoid
+    // "builderMainLoop: invalid argument" errors caused by a bug in
+    // process-1.6.16.0 (bundled with GHC 9.2.8). Fixed in 1.6.18.0.
+    // See: https://github.com/haskell/process/issues/273
+    (void)useJobObject;  // Mark as intentionally unused
+    *hJob = NULL;

     if (!CreateProcess(NULL, cmd, NULL, NULL, inherit, dwFlags, environment, workingDirectory, &sInfo, &pInfo))
     {
